  <description akvo:type="4" type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Famine response Nile Hope</narrative>
  </description>
  <description akvo:type="6" type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The food security situation in South Sudan continues to deteriorate with an estimated 5.5 million people projected to be severely food insecure by July 2017.  Leer County, where Nile Hope has been active since 2013, has been classified in Famine. Leer is also among the 14 counties with Global Acute Malnutrition (GAM) at or above 15% (SS IPC TWG).  Together, these facts present a worsening food security and nutrition situation. There is therefore an urgent need to scale up interventions in Food Security and Nutrition sectors to address the immediate needs.
Nile Hope will be providing fishing kits to 1,000 households and will also support vulnerable households on the islands with fast growing vegetables for kitchen gardening, for which the organization will also provide the necessary garden tools and equipment. In addition to these activities, Nile Hope will repair existing water points, distribute water purification tablets and train the communities on sanitation and hygiene in order to increase their awareness with regard to waterborne diseases and the importance of safe drinking water.
The organization
Nile Hope is already active in Leer County and is currently deploying several teams composed of field extension workers and FSL officers in the project region. Also technical staff, such as hand pump mechanics and hygiene promotors, has been contracted. In general Nile Hope will be deploying a total of 29 staff to the emergency response in Leer County in addition to the existing 58 staff members that are still on the ground responding to the emergency situation in the county. The organization is partnering with FAO and Concern Worldwide, among others. Nile Hope has been partner of Kerk in Actie since 2016.</narrative>
  </description>
